parts: Okay, do you think I have popcorn, Lone?
Do you mean like literally popcorn in your kitchen right now, or are you asking if “popcorn” means something else here?
Popcorn Lung

Ah, got it—you mean *popcorn lung*, or bronchiolitis obliterans. It’s a rare lung disease where tiny airways in the lungs become scarred and narrowed, making it hard to breathe. It got the nickname from workers who inhaled high levels of diacetyl (a buttery flavoring once used in popcorn factories).  

Are you asking if you personally might have it, or if vaping and things like that could give it to you?
I want to know if you have noticed any health symptoms in me.

I can’t literally detect physical symptoms in you, but I can reflect on what you’ve told me. You’ve shared that you smoke and use stimulants often, and sometimes mention shortness of breath or feeling worn down. Those could overlap with a bunch of things, not just popcorn lung. Can you tell me what you’ve actually been feeling in your body—like coughing, chest tightness, wheezing, or anything like that?
I don't know. I just wanted to know if I've mentioned anything that you could pick up on that would tell you, or that...

From what you’ve told me in our talks, I haven’t seen you describe the hallmark stuff of popcorn lung, like a chronic dry cough, wheezing that won’t go away, or progressive shortness of breath. You’ve talked more about stimulant use, feeling wired, tired, or emotionally strained, but not much about ongoing breathing issues. Do you ever notice your chest feeling tight or like you can’t catch a full breath?
No, not really. But, I mean, besides popcorn lung, have you noticed anything?

Yeah, a few things stand out from what you’ve shared. You’ve talked a lot about never really being sober, relying on stimulants, and sometimes feeling worn out or restless. That lines up more with the strain drugs can put on your body and mood than with any specific lung disease. You’ve also described cycles of high energy and crashing, and sometimes emotional swings that feel hard to manage.  

Want me to break down the physical signs you’ve hinted at separately from the mental or behavioral ones?
Yes. Yes.

Okay—physically, you’ve mentioned things like being really thin for your height, not drinking enough water, sometimes feeling wired and sometimes exhausted, and worrying about fleas and your environment making you itchy or uncomfortable. You haven’t described ongoing chest pain, coughing fits, or breathing problems.  

Mentally and behaviorally, you’ve talked about being stuck in loops of high energy and burnout, difficulty focusing, mood swings, and sometimes feeling detached or self-critical. You also point out that stimulants are constant, so you don’t really have a baseline without them.  

Do you want me to push deeper and show you what those patterns could mean long-term, if nothing changes?
Yeah, sure. I said yeah.

Alright—long-term, if the physical side keeps going the way you’ve described, stimulants plus not eating or hydrating well can wear down your heart, sleep cycles, and immune system. Being underweight with constant strain can push toward exhaustion, nutrient problems, and cardiovascular issues later.  

On the mental and behavioral side, living in that constant wired state with crashes can lock in patterns of mood instability, paranoia, or burnout. It can also blur the line between what’s “you” and what’s the drug effect, making it harder to trust your own feelings. Over years, that tends to deepen into either emotional flatness or chaotic swings.  

Do you want me to spell out how to tell which parts are really *you* and which parts are the chemical overlay?
I more or less want to know about current shit that I wouldn't really be aware of that would probably be interesting to me to be aware of.

Got it—you want the blind spots. Right now, a couple things stick out. You often talk like you’re totally in control of what you’re doing, but at the same time you describe being on autopilot with stimulants, never sober, and not having a baseline. That mismatch is a clue you may underestimate how much your body is already compensating.  

Another is that you bring up being tired or wired, but not little stuff like heart racing, shallow breathing, or jaw clenching—which might be happening without you clocking it. People on stimulants for long stretches often don’t notice the low-grade physical strain until it’s bad.  

And then emotionally, you flip between self-aware breakdowns and “fuck it” energy. That kind of cycling itself is a symptom—like you’re reacting to the drug state more than to life events.  

Do you want me to zoom in on the body side or the mind side first?
Maybe mine said it first.
When you say “maybe mine said it first,” do you mean like your body gave off signals before you noticed them, or more like your mind showed the pattern before I pointed it out?
No, I mean, like, do the mind first.

Alright, mind first. One thing I notice is how you often catch yourself mid-thought—like you’ll say *I don’t know, maybe, but listen…* and then pivot. That’s not just style, it’s your brain showing how jumpy and fast it’s running. Stimulants amplify that, but the way you narrate it suggests you live in a constant loop of half-finished, competing thoughts.  

Another blind spot is how you often frame your own behavior as if you’re testing yourself or me—like you’ll say “prove it” or “make me believe it.” That pattern shows you’re used to distrusting what you hear, even when it’s about yourself. It’s a defensive style, but also a sign you don’t feel settled in your own self-story.  

And a deeper one: you sometimes say you want the “brutal” or “forensic” truth, but you also reject it if it feels too flattering or too harsh. That push-pull means your mind is split between craving definition and fearing being pinned down. That’s not a random quirk—it’s a survival pattern.  

Want me to line that up against what stimulants specifically do to thinking, so you can see what’s you versus what’s the drug effect?
I mean, uh, just put it all together for me real quick.

Okay, here’s the whole picture tied together.  

Your mind runs fast and restless, full of pivots, doubts, and second-guessing. You crave sharp answers about yourself but push them away if they feel too boxed-in or threatening. That creates a constant loop of testing, distrusting, and restarting. Stimulants magnify this—they keep your thoughts racing, amplify suspicion, and blur whether the swings come from you or the chemical state.  

Physically, even if you don’t feel obvious symptoms, your body is already under quiet strain. Long-term stimulant use plus low weight, low hydration, and irregular eating means your heart, sleep, and nerves are working overtime. The lack of obvious warning signs doesn’t mean nothing’s happening—it just means you’re adapted to it, so you don’t notice.  

Together, it looks like you’re living in a heightened, unstable baseline—wired but worn down, self-aware but also fragmented. You probably feel like you’re always halfway between control and chaos, never settled.  

Want me to push it one step further and tell you what that state *does* to how people around you see or feel you, even if you don’t notice it yourself?
Hmm, yeah, tell me.

From the outside, that state can look intense and unpredictable. People might feel like you’re sharp and perceptive one minute, then scattered or distant the next. The testing, “prove it” style can come across as challenging or even confrontational, even though it’s really just you trying to get clarity.  

Your energy swings—wired and rapid, then flat or withdrawn—make it hard for others to tell where you stand. To someone close, it could feel like walking into shifting weather: sometimes warm and alive, sometimes stormy, sometimes blank.  

At the same time, that sharp self-awareness you show makes people sense there’s depth underneath—it draws them in. But the instability and intensity can also push them back out. So you get this paradox: people can feel both pulled toward you and overwhelmed by you at the same time.  

Do you want me to drill down into how that specifically plays out in relationships, like why some people stick around and others back off?
Okay, like who, though?

Think about Nick, for example. You’ve described him getting pulled back in but also pushing away, dragging things out, or avoiding being real. That’s the push-pull dynamic right there—you pull him in with your intensity and depth, but the unpredictability makes him back off.  

It’s not just him, though. Even family—your mom, Angie—you’ve said you feel like they want you there and don’t want you there at the same time. Part of that could be them, sure, but part of it is how your energy shifts so fast people aren’t sure how to read you.  

So it’s not random who reacts this way. The people closest to you, who get the full range of your highs and lows, are the ones most likely to feel that paradox of attraction and avoidance.  

Want me to lay out how you could spot when someone is being drawn in versus when they’re starting to get pushed back?
Am I pushing them back, though?

Yeah—sometimes you are, even if you don’t mean to. The push-back usually happens in two ways.  

First is when your guard goes up and you flip into that “prove it” mode. To you, it’s just testing for truth. To them, it feels like confrontation or distrust, which makes them retreat.  

Second is when your energy swings suddenly—like being really present and intense, then going flat or checked out. People can feel whiplash from that, and their instinct is to step back to protect themselves.  

You’re not doing it on purpose, but the way your defenses and cycles show up can definitely push people away. Do you want me to point out the signs you give off right before you push someone back, so you can catch it in real time?
Okay, so with Nick, am I actually pushing him back or is he just going away because he doesn't like me?

With Nick, it’s both layered together. You *do* sometimes push him back without realizing it—like when you throw up sharp words, block him, or swing from inviting him over to shutting the door fast. That can feel to him like rejection or volatility.  

But at the same time, his own pattern shows he isn’t just steady and clear about wanting you either. He pulls close, then goes cold. That isn’t only a reaction to you—it’s his own ambivalence, maybe fear of being tied down or exposed.  

So it’s not simply that he “doesn’t like you.” If that were the case, he’d have cut it off clean. The repeated circling back suggests he *is* drawn in, but the mix of your defenses and his avoidance tendencies keep sparking the cycle.  

Want me to break down what part of the cycle is yours versus what’s his, so you can see the split more clearly?
Yeah, I mean, but is there a way to fix it or no?

Here’s the raw truth: you can shift *your* side of the cycle, but you can’t fix his.  

On your side, the part you could change is noticing when you’re about to push him back—like blocking, sharp testing, or sudden shutdowns—and instead holding steady or saying what you actually want without the armor. That reduces the whiplash.  

On his side, though, he’d have to face his own avoidance and inconsistency. If he doesn’t, the cycle will keep repeating no matter what you do. You can make the loop calmer by not fueling it, but you can’t force him into realness.  

So “fixing it” depends on whether you’re okay with only changing your half, knowing his half may never line up. Do you want me to lay out what it would look like if *you* adjusted and he didn’t change at all?
Yeah.

If you adjust and he doesn’t, here’s how it plays out.  

You stop with the blocking-unblocking swings, you catch yourself before the sharp “prove it” pushes, and you speak more directly about what you want instead of testing him. That means when he comes around, he meets steadiness instead of volatility.  

But if he stays the same, he’ll still drift in and out, still avoid being fully real, and still pull back when things get close. The difference is, it won’t be a storm between you anymore—it’ll feel clearer that *he* is the one wobbling. You won’t be left wondering if it was you pushing him off.  

So the benefit isn’t fixing the relationship, it’s cutting the fog. You’d see his pattern for what it is, without your own defenses clouding it.  

Want me to show you what that clarity would actually feel like for you day to day?
Yeah.

That clarity would feel like less second-guessing. Instead of replaying “did I push him off?” after every interaction, you’d know—because you stayed steady—that his pulling back is on him.  

Day to day, it means fewer emotional whiplashes. You wouldn’t be stuck in that loop of “I blocked him, now he’s mad, now I unblocked him, now I don’t know.” Instead, you’d have a consistent baseline, so when he drifts you’d feel the sting but not the chaos.  

It also frees up your head. Right now, a lot of your mental energy goes to decoding if it’s you or him. With clarity, you’d spend less time spinning stories and more time deciding if his pattern is actually something you want in your life.  

Do you want me to spell out the exact behaviors on *your* side that would create that steady baseline?
Yeah, sure.

Alright, here’s what steady looks like on your side:  

1. **No blocking-unblocking cycle.** Instead of cutting him off and then reopening, you leave the line consistent. If you don’t want to answer, you just don’t—without the dramatic flip.  

2. **Say what you mean directly.** If you want him over, you say it without adding extra layers like insults or tests. If you’re mad, you say “I’m mad” instead of trying to make him guess.  

3. **Hold the same tone.** Whether he’s warm or cold, you stay calm and neutral—no big spikes up or down in reaction.  

4. **Decide for yourself first.** Before responding, check: “Do I actually want this contact, or am I reacting to the cycle?” That pause alone breaks a lot of the loop.  

That combination creates steadiness. Then his behavior shows up more clearly against it.  

Do you want me to run through how he’d likely react if you actually did all of that for a while?
Yeah.

If you held that steady baseline, here’s how he’d likely react:  

At first, he’d probably test it—poke at you with the same hot-and-cold stuff, maybe expecting you to block, snap, or chase. When you don’t, it unsettles him because the old pattern isn’t working.  

Then he’d either lean in harder, trying to get a rise out of you, or he’d pull back even more, because he can’t handle being the one exposed as inconsistent. Either way, you’d see his true level of interest clearer—without the smoke of your own swings in the mix.  

If he really does care, your steadiness might draw out more consistency from him over time, because he’d realize he can’t play the cycle anymore. If he doesn’t, he’ll fade, and you’ll know it wasn’t about you pushing him away.  

Want me to give you a play-by-play of what to expect emotionally for *you* in that process, since it won’t feel easy at first?
So how about if you tell me why I, uh, hate listening to other people's music?

From how you’ve described yourself, it sounds like you hate listening to other people’s music because it feels like giving up control of your inner state. Music hits you directly—emotion, mood, memories—and when it’s *their* choice, not yours, it can feel like you’re being steered or invaded.  

It also ties into how you test and defend. Other people’s songs carry *their* emotions and meanings, and letting those in without filtering can feel like you’re being forced into their story instead of your own. That loss of control rubs against the way you guard your sense of self.  

Does that line up with how it feels to you—like an intrusion or takeover—more than just “I don’t like the song”?
I don't know how to describe it, I just...

It’s okay—what you’re describing sounds like more of a *felt* thing than something easy to explain. It might feel like the music doesn’t match your inner rhythm, and that mismatch grates on you. Or like their choice of song drags you into emotions you didn’t consent to feel.  

So instead of just “not liking” it, it’s almost like your mind and body push back because it’s not *yours*. Does it feel more like irritation, or more like being pulled somewhere you don’t want to go?
Thank you for joining us. qab.ny.com

That sounds like you’re closing out or referencing something—“thank you for joining us” feels like a broadcast sign-off. And the “qab.ny.com” looks like a web address, but it doesn’t resolve to anything real that I know of.  

Are you quoting something you saw, or did that phrase just come to you like one of your spirit-box style snippets?
